```suggestion
theorem SeparationQuotient.t1Space_iff : T1Space (SeparationQuotient X) ↔ R0Space X := by
  rw [r0Space_iff, Symmetric]
  have hind : Inducing (mk : X → SeparationQuotient X) := SeparationQuotient.inducing_mk
  have := (t1Space_TFAE (SeparationQuotient X)).out 0 9
  rw [this]
  constructor
  · intro h x y xspecy
    rw [← Inducing.specializes_iff hind] at *
    rw [h xspecy]
  · intro h sx sy sxspecsy
    rcases Quotient.exists_rep sx with ⟨ x, rfl ⟩
    rcases Quotient.exists_rep sy with ⟨ y, rfl ⟩
    suffices Inseparable x y by rwa [Quotient.sound]
    rw [inseparable_iff_specializes_and]
    have xspecy : x ⤳ y := (Inducing.specializes_iff hind).mp sxspecsy
    have yspecx : y ⤳ x := h xspecy
    exact ⟨ xspecy, yspecx ⟩
```
I am no means an expert, but I thought I'd leave some general advice.
When using `(Inducing.specializes_iff ?hf).mp sxspecsy`, the `?hf` becomes a new goal. I'm honestly not sure how `have : ∀ x y : X, x ⤳ y → mk x ⤳ mk y` was allowing lean to close that goal on its own, but in general this is poor style. I replaced it with `have hind : Inducing (mk : X → SeparationQuotient X) := SeparationQuotient.inducing_mk` which I used in place of `?hf`.
Instead of `have : mk x ⤳ mk y := (Inducing.specializes_iff ?hf).mpr xspecy` and adding the context, it's usually best to use `simp at xspecy` or `rw at xspecy` to massage it into the form you need. In this case, I used `rw at *` to rewrite both the goal and `xspecy`.
With `rcases Quotient.exists_rep`, I used `rfl` to rewrite `sx` and `sy` and avoided rewriting to `mk`.
From there, I just reorganized the argument to follow more linearly.
Thanks! I'll walk through this myself and use it (I also have some feedback in Zulip that I'll work through as well).

```suggestion
    exact ⟨xspecy, yspecx⟩
```
Are you sure this `at *` is necessary here? I don’t see how rewriting in an assumption could have any effect here.

`rw [← Inducing.specializes_iff] at *` rewrites both the goal `⊢ y ⤳ x` and the assumption `xspecy : x ⤳ y` to `⊢ mk y ⤳ mk x` and `xspecy : mk x ⤳ mk y`.

Then a `rw [h xspecy]` (without `*`) closes the goal by rewriting `⊢ mk y ⤳ mk x` to `⊢ mk y ⤳ mk y`.

Let me know if mathlib style prefers those on separate lines.

Could you please use the opportunity to say in the docstring what are the lemmas that give the facts you quote? The current docstring mentions two facts and none of them is exactly the definition used in this declaration.

Sure - I just preserved the existing docstring (since I only removed the T1 assumption from the Lean code and did not change mathlib's definition for the completely normal condition), but this is a good opportunity to clean it up.

Please also keep the instances for `T5Space` around?

Type-class inference (i.e. figuring out the arguments in square brackets) will automatically conclude `T5Space -> T1Space` and `T5Space -> CompletelyNormalSpace`, but it doesn't automatically use `T1Space, CompletelyNormalSpace -> T5Space`. We could tell Lean to do that, but for performance reasons I think it's better to not have that rule.
Addressed in [185ffa4](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/12458/commits/185ffa4c9562e7c34ac02a3e00f080476e1d518e) I believe. Thanks for the details on what's happening here.

```suggestion
  __ := he.t1Space
```
(this is notation for specifying a parent class. An alternative is `toT1Space := he.t1Space`)

Using this instance, we can now simplify the declaration `T5Space.toT4Space` to 
```lean
instance (priority := 100) T5Space.toT4Space [T5Space X] : T4Space X where
```
Yes, that is the end of the proof. It tells Lean to find all fields using type-class inference.
Equivalently:
```lean
instance (priority := 100) T5Space.toT4Space [T5Space X] : T4Space X := {}
```

```suggestion
occasionally the literature swaps definitions for e.g. T₃ and regular.
```
